{"title_page": "Harold Ford Jr.", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Harold Ford|his father, the congressman from Tennessee from 1975 to 1997|Harold Ford Sr.}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image       = Harold Ford, Congressional photo portrait.jpg\n|state       = [[Tennessee]]\n|district    = {{ushr|TN|9|9th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 1997\n|term_end    = January 3, 2007\n|predecessor = [[Harold Ford Sr.]]\n|successor   = [[Steve Cohen]]\n|birth_name  = Harold Eugene Ford Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1970|5|11}}\n|birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]], U.S.\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Emily Threlkeld (2008\u2013present)\n|children    = 2\n|education   = [[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Michigan]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|haroldfordjr.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Harold Eugene Ford Jr.''' (born May 11, 1970)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=F000262 |title=FORD, Harold, Jr. - Biographical Information |website=bioguide.congress.gov}}</ref> is an American financial managing director, [[pundit]], author, and former U.S. congressman who served from 1997&ndash;2007 in the [[United States House of Representatives]] as a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] from {{ushr|Tennessee|9}}, centered in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]]. He is the son of former Congressman [[Harold Ford Sr.]], who held the same seat for 22 years. In 2006, Ford made an [[2006 United States Senate election in Tennessee|unsuccessful bid]] for the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] seat vacated by retiring [[Bill Frist]]. He is a member of the [[Ford family (Memphis)|Ford political family]] from Memphis. Ford was the last chairman of the [[Democratic Leadership Council]] (DLC).<ref name=NYT100106>Barbaro, Michael, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/06/nyregion/06ford.html \"Harold Ford Jr. Weighs a Challenge to Gillibrand\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 5, 2010</ref>\n\nBetween 2011 and 2017, Ford  worked for [[Morgan Stanley]] as a managing director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.morganstanley.com/press-releases/former-us-congressman-harold-ford-jr-joins-morgan-stanley_6b2c1335-7508-495c-aba7-6ce3d14cc42b|title=Former U.S. Congressman Harold Ford, Jr. Joins Morgan Stanley|website=Morgan Stanley}}</ref> He also regularly appeared on television on political-related programs, such as [[NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'', [[MSNBC]], [[CNN]], [[CNBC]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Meet the Press|title=Former Rep. Harold Ford (D-TN) on Meet the Press On the Keystone XL Pipeline|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LVQQF2y6oAU|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref> He and his wife live in New York City and have a daughter, Georgia Walker,<ref name=\"page6\">{{cite news|url=http://pagesix.com/2013/12/24/its-a-girl/  |title=It's a girl! |last=Smith |first=Emily |date=24 December 2013 |work=Page Six |publisher=2015 NYP Holdings, Inc. |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> and a son, Harold Eugene III.<ref name=\"memfly1\" />\n\nFord also wrote a book, ''More Davids Than Goliaths: A Political Education'', published in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/More-Davids-Than-Goliaths-Political/dp/B008SLNYUG |title=More Davids Than Goliaths: A Political Education |accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Family and education==\nFord was born in Memphis, Tennessee, the eldest son of former Representative [[Harold Ford Sr.]] and Dorothy Bowles Ford.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wargs.com/political/fordh.html |title=Ancestry of Harold Ford |first=William Addams |last=Reitwiesner |accessdate=2007-05-18}}</ref> He has two brothers, Jake and Isaac, as well as two [[Sibling#Half-sibling|half-siblings]], Andrew and Ava, from his father's second marriage.\n\nThe Ford family has long been prominent in Memphis' African-American community. Ford's grandfather, N.J. Ford, established a funeral home, which gave the family a broad network in the community. [[E.H. Crump]], a prominent white Democrat, dominated city and state politics in the early 20th century and befriended N.J. Ford.<ref>{{cite news |date=2005-08-01 |accessdate=2007-05-18 |url=http://www.tennessean.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050801/NEWS0201/508010361/1010/NEWS02/ |title=Political future of Fords hinges on constituents |first=Bonna |last=de la Cruz |work=[[The Tennessean]]}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Ford's uncle is [[John Ford (Tennessee politician)|John N. Ford]], who is Harold Sr.'s brother and was a member of the [[Tennessee State Senate]] until he was convicted on federal bribery charges in 2007 as part of the [[Operation Tennessee Waltz|Operation Tennessee Waltz scandal]].\n\nFord lived the first years of his life within the living quarters of his family-owned business N.J. Ford And Sons Funeral Home, which at the time was located in the [[Riverside, South Memphis|Riverside]] neighborhood. He was [[baptism|baptized]] at his family church, Mt. Moriah-East Baptist Church. He attended Double Tree Elementary School, a public [[Montessori school]] in the [[Westwood, Memphis, Tennessee|Westwood]] neighborhood, but graduated from the private [[St. Albans School (Washington, D.C.)|St. Albans School]] for Boys, a prestigious [[university-preparatory school]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], which he attended after his father became a Congressman. He went on to earn a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in American history from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1992.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web |url=http://www.house.gov/ford/about/index.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060902094237/http://www.house.gov/ford/about/index.shtml |archive-date=2006-09-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Early career and legal education==\nAfter graduation, Ford went into government, serving as a staff aide to the [[U.S. Senate Committee on the Budget|Senate Budget Committee]]. In 1993, he became special assistant at the [[United States Department of Commerce]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=F000262 |title=Ford, Harold Jr. |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |accessdate=2007-05-18}}</ref>\n\nFord returned to university for a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from the [[University of Michigan Law School]] in 1996. During his campaign for the House of Representatives, he sat for and failed the Tennessee [[bar exam]]; he said that he intended to try again.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.metropulse.com/dir_zine/dir_2004/1423/t_cover.html |title=Harold Ford Jr., Prince of Memphis |first=Roger |last=Abramson |newspaper=Nashville Scene |date=2004-06-03 |accessdate=2007-05-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520010056/http://www.metropulse.com/dir_zine/dir_2004/1423/t_cover.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=2007-05-20}}</ref>\n\n==House of Representatives career==\nWhen Harold Sr. decided not to seek a 12th term in Congress in 1996, Harold Jr. entered the race and became the favorite in the Democratic primary, which was widely regarded as the real contest in the heavily Democratic, black-majority 9th district. Ford arranged his schedule for his last semester of law school so he would not have Monday or Friday classes<ref name=\"Rising star\">{{cite web |url=http://www.democrats.org/a/2006/08/harold_fords_ri.php |title=Harold Ford's Rising Star Heads Toward the Senate |publisher=Democratic Party |date=August 2006 |accessdate=2007-05-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927020524/http://www.democrats.org/a/2006/08/harold_fords_ri.php |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and would be able to fly home to Memphis for an extended weekend each week to continue his campaign. As was expected, he easily won the Democratic [[primary election|primary]], followed by his election in November. Taking office at the age of 26, he was one of the [[List of youngest members of the United States Congress|youngest members of Congress]] in US history and the youngest in the 105th and 106th Congresses. He was reelected four times without substantive [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] opposition, by an average of 80 percent of the vote. In 2000, Ford was the [[keynote]] speaker for the [[2000 Democratic National Convention]] supporting then [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Al Gore]] for the Democratic nomination for [[President of the United States|President]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=CNN |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/08/16/ford.speech/index.html |title=Ford appeals to younger voters in keynote address |first=Mike |last=Ferullo |date=2000-08-16 |accessdate=2007-05-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108024844/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/08/16/ford.speech/index.html |archivedate=2007-01-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 1999, Ford voted in favor of the [[Gramm\u2013Leach\u2013Bliley Act]],.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/vote.xpd?vote=h1999-570|title=S. 900 (106th): Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act -- House Vote #570 -- Nov 4, 1999|website=GovTrack.us}}</ref> This act repealed much of the [[Glass\u2013Steagall Act of 1933]], which had been enacted to prevent any one organization from acting as any combination of an investment bank, a commercial bank, and an insurance company. The resulting repeal allowed many banks and insurance companies to gamble with money raised from savings and checking bank accounts or insurance policies. Several economists, notably [[Nobel laureate]] [[Joseph Stiglitz]], point to the repeal of Glass\u2013Steagall as helping to create the conditions of the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132010|2007 financial crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/print?id=5835269|title=Who's Whining Now? Economists Hit Gramm|website=abcnews.go.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB123665023774979341 |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=Ten Questions for Those Fixing the Financial Mess |first1=Damian |last1=Paletta |first2=Kara |last2=Scannell |date=March 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2002, he was among the 81 House Democrats who voted in favor of authorizing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].\n\nAfter the Democrats lost seven Congressional seats in the [[2002 United States House of Representatives elections|2002 elections]], Ford announced his candidacy for House Democratic Leader, challenging then-[[House Minority Whip]] [[Nancy Pelosi]], arguing that current leadership was ineffective.<ref>phttp://www.tnr.com/doc.mhtml?i=20021125&s=lizza112502] {{dead link|date=October 2018}}</ref> Ford was defeated but exceeded initial expectations in the amount of support he received.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/11/14/democrats.leadership/ |publisher=CNN |title=Democrats pick Pelosi as House leader |date=November 14, 2002 |accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref> Although his name was mentioned as a possible Democratic vice presidential candidate in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/miller/miller200402120825.asp|title=John J. Miller on Election 2004 & Vice President on National Review Online<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=nationalreview.com}}</ref>  he was ineligible for the office due to his age (four months shy of 35 on [[Inauguration Day]] 2005).\n\nA June 7, 2005, article in ''[[The Washington Times]]'' reported that from 1998 to 2003, Ford took 61 privately funded trips but did not file travel disclosure forms with the House clerk for the trips, as required by the chamber's ethics rules, until August 2003. Ford's office called the late filings a \"mere oversight\", since Ford had filed the required financial disclosure statements for the trips at the time they occurred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washtimes.com/national/20050607-121908-6262r.htm|title=Lawmakers dash to correct records of trips|newspaper=[[The Washington Times]]}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, when Ohio Republican Congresswoman [[Jean Schmidt]] implied that Pennsylvania Democrat [[John Murtha]] was a \"coward\" in response to Murtha's proposal for a withdrawal of American forces from [[Iraq]], Ford charged across the House floor to the Republican side during the resulting uproar in the chamber, shouting \"Say it to Murtha!\" (or \"Say Murtha's name!\" depending on the source) while waving his finger at Schmidt. He had to be restrained by fellow Democrat [[Dave Obey]] of [[Wisconsin]]. Like many Democrats, Ford believed Schmidt's remarks (which she later withdrew) were an unwarranted \"cheap shot\" against Murtha, a veteran of the [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]].<ref>[[Howard Fineman|Fineman, Howard]], [http://www.newsweek.com/id/51199 \"Bush at the Tipping Point\"], ''[[Newsweek]]'', November 28, 2005</ref>\n\n[[File:Haroldfdjrcampaigning.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Harold Ford Jr. on the campaign trail]]\nIn Congress, Ford opposed benefits for same-sex couples and supported the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], which would have defined marriage as one man and one woman. He told Democrats they should be more supportive of the [[Iraq War]], and criticized Senate Democrats who attempted to [[filibuster]] the nomination of [[Samuel Alito]]. He was one of the few Democrats who voted for the [[Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act|bankruptcy bill]], and he defined himself as a [[pro-life]] candidate, supporting some restrictions on [[abortion]], including a ban on [[intact dilation and extraction]], called \"partial-birth abortion\" by opponents. However, the [[National Right to Life Committee]] says that while in Congress he voted against the pro-life position 87% of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrlc.org/election2006/FordNotProLife.html|title=Harold Ford Jr., Is Not Pro-Life|website=Nrlc.org|access-date=2010-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061201011928/http://www.nrlc.org/election2006/FordNotProLife.html|archive-date=2006-12-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>  He supported the Republican effort to intercede in the [[Terri Schiavo case]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/f000262/key-votes/ |title=Key Votes |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref> He opposed President [[George W. Bush]]'s energy proposals (including oil drilling in [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]]), demonstrated support for [[adoption]] rights of [[same-sex couples]], is in favor of federal funding of [[embryonic stem cell]] research, supported [[universal healthcare coverage]], opposed the [[death penalty]] and indicated a willingness to reform [[drug policy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Harold_Ford.htm|title=Harold Ford on the Issues|website=Ontheissues.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fordfortennessee.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=34 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060906183445/http://www.fordfortennessee.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=34 |archive-date=2006-09-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Ford sat on the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|House Budget Committee]] and the [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|House Committee on Financial Services]]. He also served on the Transformation Advisory Group, a group of political, military and academic leaders who worked with the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] to assess the needs of the armed forces. Ford was a member of the [[New Democrat Coalition]], the [[Congressional Black Caucus]] and the [[Blue Dog Coalition]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 2002, Ford was mentioned as a possible Democratic candidate for the Senate seat being vacated by [[Fred Thompson]], but he declined to run. Instead, he supported fellow Congressman [[Bob Clement]] who would lose to former Republican Governor [[Lamar Alexander]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/03/17/tipper.senate/index.html|title=CNN - Breaking News, Latest News and Videos|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Ford did not run for re-election to the House of Representatives, due to his campaign for the [[United States Senate]] in Tennessee, which he lost. His younger brother, Jake Ford, ran for the [[Tennessee's 9th congressional district|9th district seat]] as an Independent, but lost to Democrat [[Steve Cohen]].\n\n==2006 Tennessee Senate campaign==\n{{Main|2006 United States Senate election in Tennessee}}\nOn April 6, 2005, during an interview on [[C-SPAN]]'s call-in show ''[[Washington Journal]]'', Ford confirmed that he would be running for the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-span.org/search/basic.asp?ResultStart=1&ResultCount=10&BasicQueryText=harold+ford+senate&image1.x=0&image1.y=0&image1=Submit|title=C-SPAN.org: Search Results<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=C-span.org}}</ref> He filed the papers necessary to officially begin his Senate campaign on May 25, 2005.\n\nDemocratic State Senator [[Rosalind Kurita]] briefly challenged Ford for the nomination but dropped out of the primary because of inadequate fundraising, effectively handing Ford the nomination.<ref>[http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_83648.asp 4/12/2006 - Rosalind Kurita Withdraws From U.S. Senate Race] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825174005/http://www.chattanoogan.com/articles/article_83648.asp |date=2006-08-25 }}, ''[[The Chattanoogan]]''</ref> On August 3, 2006, Ford overwhelmingly won the Democratic primary. After the primary, Ford's supporters held a large victory celebration at [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]]'s [[LP Field]]. Among the speakers was former [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Bill Clinton]].\n\nFord faced Republican [[Bob Corker]] in the November 2006 election. Not long after Corker's primary victory was assured, Ford challenged Corker to seven televised debates across the state. In response, Corker said he would debate Ford, though he did not agree to seven debates.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}\n\nIn October 2006, <!-- removed following text and dead link \u2192as polls indicated that Ford maintained a slight lead in the Senate race,<ref>[http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/politics/elections/senate_races/tennessee_senate_ford_d_48_corker_r_46 Tennessee Senate: Ford (D) 48%; Corker (R) 46%] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201141330/http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/politics/elections/senate_races/tennessee_senate_ford_d_48_corker_r_46 |date=December 1, 2008 }}, ''Rasmussen Reports'', October 13, 2006.</ref>\u2190 end text removal. If re-adding, this link was good a/o 2010-02-23 for poll results over the course of the campaign: http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2006/senate/tn/tennessee_senate_race-20.html#polls -->\nthe Republican Party ran radio and television ads characterized by some as racially tinged. A radio spot, referred to by critics as the \"jungle drums\" ad, had drums playing when Ford's name was mentioned and patriotic music when Corker's name was spoken. This ad was criticized as attacking Ford's race by evoking images of primitive, chanting African tribes.<ref>Sargent, Greg, [http://tpmelectioncentral.talkingpointsmemo.com/2006/10/tnsen_corker_radio_ad_has_jung.php \"TN-SEN: Corker Radio Ad Has \"Jungle Drums\" During Mentions Of Ford\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716191200/http://tpmelectioncentral.talkingpointsmemo.com/2006/10/tnsen_corker_radio_ad_has_jung.php |date=2011-07-16 }}, ''[[Talking Points Memo]]'', October 25, 2006, Retrieved February 23, 2010</ref> A [[2006 Tennessee United States Senate election#Controversy|television ad that received more attention]] featured satirical \"man\u2011on\u2011the\u2011street\" interviews purporting to support Ford, including one in which a blond white woman (implied to be nude) talks about meeting Ford at \"the Playboy party\"; she returns at the end of the ad to wink and whisper in a seductive tone, \"Harold, call me.\" The ad was denounced by many people, including Republican former Senator [[William Cohen]], who called it \"a very serious appeal to a [[racism|racist]] sentiment\", and Corker asked the Republican leadership to pull the ad. The ad was retired one day after [[Republican National Committee]] Chairman [[Ken Mehlman]] said he had no authority to discontinue the ad and disagreed with the negative characterizations of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cWkrwENN5CQ|title=Too Hot For Corker|author=A.C. Kleinheider|date=21 October 2006|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>Johnson, Alex, [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15403071 \"Tennessee ad ignites internal GOP squabbling\"], [[NBC News]], October 25, 2006, Retrieved February 23, 2010</ref><ref>O\u2019Donnell, Norah, [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15418962 \"GOP retires \u2018Playboy\u2019 ad in Tennessee\"], NBC News, October 25, 2006, Retrieved February 23, 2010</ref>\n\nCorker and Ford participated in a televised debate in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] on October 7, in Corker's hometown of Chattanooga on October 10, and in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] on October 28. In January 2006, [[NBC]]'s ''[[Meet the Press]]'' extended an open invitation for the candidates to debate on the nationally televised show.\n\nOn November 8, Ford conceded the election to Corker, who defeated Ford by less than three percentage points.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2006/pages/results/states/TN/S/01/index.html |publisher=CNN |title=Elections 2006 |accessdate=May 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Post-congressional activities==\nIn December 2006, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' reported that Ford told students at an L.A.-area school that he might run again in 2008 for the Senate seat held by Republican [[Lamar Alexander]], but in January 2007 Ford said that he had no plans to challenge the [[incumbent]].<ref>Richard Locker, \"Another Senate seat might tempt Ford\", ''The Commercial Appeal'', December 11, 2006</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ford says he has no plans of a Senate bid against Alexander |url=http://www.wmcstations.com/Global/story.asp?S=5951146 |publisher=WMCTV.com |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=2007-01-23 |accessdate=2007-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927043434/http://www.wmcstations.com/Global/story.asp?S=5951146 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> Instead, Ford has said that he \"hopes to spend a lot of time at home, perhaps do some teaching and work with [[Phil Bredesen|Governor Bredesen]] on some issues in Tennessee.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Corker sworn in as U.S. Senator|date=January 4, 2007<!-- 04:11 PM CST-->|url=http://www.wreg.com/Global/story.asp?S=5892999|publisher=Associated Press}} Retrieved on Jan. 7, 2007</ref>\n\nOn January 25, 2007, Ford was named chairman of the [[Democratic Leadership Council]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dlc.org/ndol_ci.cfm?kaid=137&subid=900145&contentid=254175 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927011643/http://www.dlc.org/ndol_ci.cfm?kaid=137&subid=900145&contentid=254175 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Ford joined the financial services firm [[Merrill Lynch]] as a vice chairman and senior policy adviser.<ref>Keoun, Bradley,[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aZjF2XoNZc88&refer=home Merrill Hires Former U.S. Congressman Ford as Adviser], Bloomberg.com, February 14, 2007.</ref><ref>Merrill Lynch (2007-02-14). Former Congressman Harold E. Ford Jr. Joins Merrill Lynch as Vice Chairman. Merrill Lynch press release, 14 February 2007. Retrieved from http://www.ml.com/index.asp?id=7695_7696_8149_74412_75268_75567 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102053136/http://ml.com/index.asp?id=7695_7696_8149_74412_75268_75567 |date=2010-01-02 }}.</ref> In the same month he was hired by [[Fox News Channel]] as a political contributor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/ford-junior-to-become-fair-and-balanced-commentator/Content?oid=1134280|title=Ford Junior To Become \"Fair and Balanced\" Commentator|first=Flyer|last=Staff|website=Memphis Flyer}}</ref> In March 2008, he moved from Fox to [[MSNBC]] as a news analyst, appearing as a panelist on [[David Gregory (journalist)|David Gregory]]'s ''[[Race for the White House]]'', ''[[Hardball with Chris Matthews|Hardball]]'', and ''[[Morning Joe]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/the_revolving_door/harold_ford_jr_jumps_from_fnc_to_msnbc_80636.asp |title=Harold Ford Jr. Jumps From FNC to MSNBC |publisher=mediabistro.com |date=2008-03-24 |accessdate=2008-03-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012175550/http://www.mediabistro.com/tvnewser/the_revolving_door/harold_ford_jr_jumps_from_fnc_to_msnbc_80636.asp |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFord was appointed visiting professor of public policy at [[Vanderbilt University]] in 2007 and taught a class on American political leadership.<ref>[http://www.vanderbilt.edu/news/releases/2007/1/15/harold-ford-jr-to-be-visiting-professor-of-public-policy-at-vanderbilt-congressional-veteran-to-teach-class-on-political-leadership Vanderbilt News Service] Harold Ford Jr. to be visiting professor of public policy at Vanderbilt; Congressional veteran to teach class on political leadership. 1/15/2007</ref> In October 2007, Ford was appointed as the inaugural Barbara Jordan Visiting Professor at the [[Lyndon B. Johnson School of Public Affairs]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utexas.edu/lbj/news/fall2007/bj_ford.php|title=LBJ School of Public Affairs Announces Appointment of Congressman Harold Ford Jr. Inaugural Barbara Jordan Visiting Professor|website=Utexas.edu|accessdate=3 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071108213007/http://www.utexas.edu/lbj/news/fall2007/bj_ford.php|archive-date=8 November 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  As of the spring 2010 semester, he is a visiting professor at [[New York University|New York University's]] [[Robert F. Wagner Graduate School of Public Service|Wagner School of Public Service]] where he teaches Policy Formation: U.S. Domestic Policy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Cabrera, Debra|date=2009-11-05|title=PNP Course Highlights: Spring 2010|url=http://wagner.nyu.edu/courses/files/CourseHighlightsPNPSp10.pdf|format=PDF|website=Wagner.nyu.edu|accessdate=3 October 2018}}</ref> In the fall of 2015 he was a visiting faculty member at the University of Michigan Ford School of Public Policy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://fordschool.umich.edu/faculty/harold-ford |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-09-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915101639/http://fordschool.umich.edu/faculty/harold-ford |archive-date=2015-09-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFord worked at the Wall Street firm [[Morgan Stanley]] as a managing director.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/41723393|last=Faber|first=David|title=Harold Ford Jr. Leaving BofA for Morgan Stanley|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref> In late 2017, erroneous media reports said that he was fired for sexual misconduct<ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite web|last1=Atkinson|first1=Claire|title=Harold Ford Jr. blasts misconduct claim that led to firing by Morgan Stanley|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/harold-ford-jr-blasts-misconduct-claim-led-firing-morgan-stanley-n827471|publisher=NBC|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite news|last1=Ali|first1=Yashar|title=Exclusive: Former Congressman Harold Ford Jr. Fired For Misconduct By Morgan Stanley|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/former-congressman-harold-ford-jr-173325565.html|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref> and Morgan Stanley issued a statement the following month saying that no sexual misconduct took place.<ref name=\"Page Six\">{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Richard|title=Vindicated Harold Ford Jr. goes after Morgan Stanley|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/01/14/vindicated-harold-ford-jr-goes-after-morgan-stanley/|publisher=Page Six|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Kate|title=Morgan Stanley Says Harold Ford Jr. Wasn\u2019t Fired for Sexual Misconduct|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/22/business/morgan-stanley-harold-ford-sexual-misconduct.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 January 2018|accessdate=15 April 2018}}</ref> In January 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that Ford reached a legal settlement with Morgan Stanley.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelly |last2=Sorkin |first1=Kate |first2=Andrew |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/11/business/dealbook/harold-ford-morgan-stanley.html |title=A Wall St. Executive\u2019s Downfall Seemed Sudden. It Was Years in the Making. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 11, 2018 |accessdate=January 20, 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"The New York Times\"/>\n\nFord is on the Board of Selectors of [[Jefferson Awards for Public Service]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeffersonawards.org/board |title=Jefferson Awards Foundation |accessdate=2013-12-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140822190847/http://www.jeffersonawards.org/board |archivedate=2014-08-22}}</ref> He is also a member of the ReFormers Caucus of [[Issue One]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.issueone.org/reformers/|title=Issue One \u2013 ReFormers Caucus|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==2010 New York Senate election==\n{{see also|2010 United States Senate special election in New York}}\nFord considered a [[Primary election|primary]] challenge to Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] in [[United States Senate special election in New York, 2010|New York in 2010]].<ref name=NYT100106 /> Sources close to Mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] of New York have said that he would consider supporting someone \"of Mr. Ford's stature\".<ref name=NYT100106 /> However, it was also reported that Mayor Bloomberg \"reassured [[Harry Reid|Mr. Reid]] that he was not personally involved in the effort to promote a Ford candidacy.\"<ref Name=NYT100107 /> [[Chuck Schumer]] sought to dissuade Ford from running.<ref Name=NYT100107>Barbaro, Michael and Hernandez, Raymond (January 7, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/08/nyregion/08ford.html?hp \"Potential Ford Senate Bid Sets Off Scramble\"], ''The New York Times'', Retrieved March 1, 2010.</ref> Ford's spokesperson on January 11, 2010, stated Ford had become a supporter of [[same-sex marriage]] after \"listening to the debate in state legislatures across the country\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dicker|first=Fredric U.|author2=Haberman, Maggie|title=Now Harold Ford Jr. backs gay marriage|newspaper=[[New York Post]]|date=January 11, 2010|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/now_ford_comes_out_for_gay_nups_VASWuxve4ht5Y4aZM8K5dJ|accessdate=January 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2010, Gillibrand held a press conference at which she raised questions as to whether Ford, as an executive of Merril Lynch, received taxpayer-backed bonuses from Bank of America, stemming from the [[Bank of America#Federal bailout|federal bailout]]. She was joined by [[New York City Public Advocate]] [[Bill de Blasio]], who endorsed her candidacy.<ref>Paybarah, Azi (February 5, 2010), [http://www.observer.com/2010/politics/gillibrand-disclosing-bonus-essential-ford \"Gillibrand: Disclosing Bonus is 'Essential' for Ford\"], ''[[The New York Observer]]'', Retrieved February 14, 2010</ref>\n\nOn February 12, it was reported that Ford's NBC contract was suspended due to his potential campaign, and that he had taken an unpaid leave of absence from Merrill Lynch for the same reason.<ref>Calderone, Michael (February 12, 2010), [http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0210/Fords_NBC_contract_suspended.html \"Ford's NBC contract suspended\"], ''[[The Politico]]'', Retrieved February 14, 2010</ref> On March 1, Ford stated in an [[op-ed]] article published by ''[[The New York Times]]'' that he would not run against Gillibrand.<ref>Ford, Harold Jr. (March 1, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/02/opinion/02ford2.html \"Why I\u2019m Not Running for the Senate\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Retrieved March 1, 2010</ref><ref>Bacon, Perry Jr. (March 2, 2010) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/01/AR2010030103669.html \"Ford won't challenge Gillibrand for Senate in N.Y.\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', Retrieved March 2, 2010</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFord married Emily Threlkeld, who works in public relations for [[Carolina Herrera (fashion designer)|Carolina Herrera]] in New York, on April 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurweb.com/story/eur42868.cfm|title=Black Entertainment News - EURWeb.com|first=Electronic Urban|last=Report|website=EURweb}}</ref> They have a daughter, Georgia Walker Ford, who was born in December 2013 in New York City. She is named for Ford's great-grandmother Georgia, and Threlkeld's mother's maiden name, Walker.<ref name=\"page6\"/> Their second child, a son, Harold Eugene Ford III, was born in May 2015.<ref name=\"memfly1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/JacksonBaker/archives/2015/06/01/harold-ford-jr-for-mayor |title=Harold Ford Jr. for Mayor?|date=June 1, 2015 |accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ {{ushr|Tennessee|9|}}: Results 1996\u20132004<ref name=\"clerkresults\">{{cite web |url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |title=Election Statistics |accessdate=2007-08-08 |publish